ass="shortdescription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style="display:none">Television-related events in the US during 2021

ass="mw-empty-elt">

able class="sidebar nomobile nowraplinks" style="line-height:2em">ass="sidebar-heading"> <a href="/wiki/List_of_years_in_American_television" title="List of years in American television">List of years in American televisiona>:ass="sidebar-content hlist">

ass="sidebar-content hlist">
ass="sidebar-content hlist"> <a href="/wiki/List_of_2021_American_television_debuts" title="List of 2021 American television debuts">List of 2021 American television debutsa> ass="sidebar-content hlist"> <a href="/wiki/2020%E2%80%9321_United_States_network_television_schedule" title="2020--21 United States network television schedule">2020--21 United States network television schedule a> ass="sidebar-content hlist"> <a href="/wiki/2021%E2%80%9322_United_States_network_television_schedule" title="2021--22 United States network television schedule">2021--22 United States network television schedule a> ass="sidebar-content hlist"> <a href="/wiki/List_of_American_television_programs_currently_in_production" title="List of American television programs currently in production">List of American television programs currently in productiona> able>

The following is a list of events affecting <a href="/wiki/American_television" class="mw-redirect" title="American television">American televisiona> in 2021. Events listed include television show debuts- finales- and cancellations; channel launches- closures- and re-brandings; stations changing or adding their network affiliations; and information about controversies and <a href="/wiki/Carriage_disputes" class="mw-redirect" title="Carriage disputes">carriage disputesa>.

a property="mw:PageProp/toc" />

an class="mw-headline" id="Notable_events">Notable eventsan>an class="mw-editsection">an class="mw-editsection-bracket">[an><a href="/w/index.php?title=2021_in_American_television&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Notable events">edita>an class="mw-editsection-bracket">]an>an>

an class="mw-headline" id="January">Januaryan>an class="mw-editsection">an class="mw-editsection-bracket">[an><a href="/w/index.php?title=2021_in_American_television&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: January">edita>an class="mw-editsection-bracket">]an>an>

able class="wikitable"> Date Event Source 6 Due to news coverage of the <a href="/wiki/January_6_United_States_Capitol_attack" title="January 6 United States Capitol attack">attack on the U.S. Capitola> in <a href="/wiki/Washington_D.C." class="mw-redirect" title="Washington D.C.">Washington D.C.a>- Broadcast networks <a href="/wiki/American_Broadcasting_Company" title="American Broadcasting Company">ABCa>- <a href="/wiki/CBS" title="CBS">CBSa> and <a href="/wiki/NBC" title="NBC">NBCa> swap its primetime schedule for continuing news coverage- while <a href="/wiki/Fox_Broadcasting_Company" title="Fox Broadcasting Company">Foxa> and <a href="/wiki/The_CW" title="The CW">The CWa> carry their normal lineups during that evening. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">[1]a> 8 <a href="/wiki/Jeopardy!" title="Jeopardy!">Jeopardy!a> airs the final episode (pushed back from <a href="/wiki/Christmas_Day" class="mw-redirect" title="Christmas Day">Christmas Daya>) of <a href="/wiki/Alex_Trebek" title="Alex Trebek">Alex Trebeka>'s hosting tenure- recorded 10 days before his November 8- 2020- death from stage IV <a href="/wiki/Pancreatic_cancer" title="Pancreatic cancer">pancreatic cancera>. Starting with the January 11 episode and for the rest of the season- a series of guest hosts- the first being highest-winning Jeopardy! champion <a href="/wiki/Ken_Jennings" title="Ken Jennings">Ken Jenningsa>- fill in at the host lectern Trebek had occupied for 36 years. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">[2]a> an="2">10 While sister network <a href="/wiki/NFL_on_CBS" title="NFL on CBS">CBSa> airs an <a href="/wiki/2020%E2%80%9321_NFL_playoffs" title="2020--21 NFL playoffs">NFL playoffa> between the <a href="/wiki/2020_Chicago_Bears_season" title="2020 Chicago Bears season">Chicago Bearsa> and <a href="/wiki/2020_New_Orleans_Saints_season" title="2020 New Orleans Saints season">New Orleans Saintsa>- <a href="/wiki/Nickelodeon" title="Nickelodeon">Nickelodeona> airs a special children-oriented version of the game. The broadcast added classic Nickelodeon gags such as <a href="/wiki/Computer_generated_imagery" class="mw-redirect" title="Computer generated imagery">CGIa>-created slime cannons "spraying" the end zones after touchdowns; prerecorded explanations of penalties- offered by <a href="/wiki/Young_Sheldon" title="Young Sheldon">Young Sheldona> star <a href="/wiki/Iain_Armitage" title="Iain Armitage">Iain Armitagea>; and announcer and former NFL star <a href="/wiki/Nate_Burleson" title="Nate Burleson">Nate Burlesona> analogizing successful plays with such childhood activities as staying in school. Although Nickelodeon's broadcast was aimed at younger- new-to-football viewers- it was reportedly enjoyed more so by <a href="/wiki/Generation_X" title="Generation X">Generation Xa> and <a href="/wiki/Millennials" title="Millennials">millenniala> parents who grew up watching the channel in its 1980s/1990s heyday. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">[3]a> The <a href="/wiki/1st_Critics%27_Choice_Super_Awards" title="1st Critics' Choice Super Awards">1st Critics' Choice Super Awardsa>- an event honoring films in the <a href="/wiki/Science_fiction_film" title="Science fiction film">science fictiona>- <a href="/wiki/Action_film" title="Action film">actiona>- <a href="/wiki/Horror_film" title="Horror film">horrora> and <a href="/wiki/Superhero_film" title="Superhero film">superheroa> genres- airs on <a href="/wiki/The_CW" title="The CW">The CWa>. The virtual ceremony saw <a href="/wiki/The_Boys_(TV_series)" title="The Boys (TV series)">The Boysa> as the top winner with four awards (including "Best Superhero Series"). ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">[4]a> 22 <a href="/wiki/Tom_Brokaw" title="Tom Brokaw">Tom Brokawa> announces his retirement from <a href="/wiki/NBC_News" title="NBC News">NBC Newsa>. A special correspondent and commentator since ending a 22-year run as <a href="/wiki/NBC_Nightly_News" title="NBC Nightly News">Nightly Newsa> anchor in 2004- Brokaw spent 55 years with <a href="/wiki/NBC" title="NBC">NBCa>- including roles as anchor/reporter at <a href="/wiki/Owned-and-operated_station" title="Owned-and-operated station">O&amp;Oa> <a href="/wiki/KNBC" title="KNBC">KNBCa>/<a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles" title="Los Angeles">Los Angelesa>- <a href="/wiki/White_House" title="White House">White Housea> correspondent- co-anchor of <a href="/wiki/Today_(American_TV_program)" title="Today (American TV program)">Todaya>- and interim moderator (after <a href="/wiki/Tim_Russert" title="Tim Russert">Tim Russerta>'s 2008 death) of <a href="/wiki/Meet_The_Press" class="mw-redirect" title="Meet The Press">Meet The Pressa>. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">[5]a> 23 <a href="/wiki/Food_Network" title="Food Network">Food Networka> pulls all content related to <a href="/wiki/Worst_Cooks_in_America#Season_20:_2020" title="Worst Cooks in America">season 20a> of <a href="/wiki/Worst_Cooks_in_America" title="Worst Cooks in America">Worst Cooks in Americaa> (which aired in Summer 2020) from its linear- streaming and social platforms (including <a href="/wiki/Discovery%2B" title="Discovery+">discovery+a>)- after season winner Ariel Robinson and her husband- Austin Robinson- were charged in the January 14 death of their adopted three-year-old daughter at their <a href="/wiki/Simpsonville-_South_Carolina" title="Simpsonville- South Carolina">Simpsonville- South Carolinaa>- home. Ariel Robinson would be convicted and sentenced to life in prison for homicide by child abuse in May 2022- one month after Austin had pleaded guilty to aiding and abetting in the killing. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">[6]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">[7]a> 25 Two top executives of the <a href="/wiki/CBS_Television_Stations" class="mw-redirect" title="CBS Television Stations">CBS Television Stationsa> group- division president Peter Dunn and Senior VP/News David Friend- are placed on administrative leave after a <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles_Times" title="Los Angeles Times">Los Angeles Timesa> investigation reveals- among other allegations- their discriminatory and disparaging behavior concerning Black and female news employees at the station level- in particular at <a href="/wiki/KYW-TV" title="KYW-TV">KYW-TVa>/<a href="/wiki/Philadelphia" title="Philadelphia">Philadelphiaa>. CBS would commission a third-party investigation into the matter and the broad culture within the station division; by the time it concludes in July- both Dunn and Friend would depart CBS (on April 7)- and the general managers at CBS stations in <a href="/wiki/Chicago" title="Chicago">Chicagoa> (<a href="/wiki/WBBM-TV" title="WBBM-TV">WBBM-TVa>) and <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles" title="Los Angeles">Los Angelesa> (<a href="/wiki/KCBS-TV" title="KCBS-TV">KCBS-TVa>/<a href="/wiki/KCAL-TV" title="KCAL-TV">KCAL-TVa>) would be dismissed. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">[8]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">[9]a>
ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">[10]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">[11]a>
ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">[12]a> able>

an class="mw-headline" id="February">Februaryan>an class="mw-editsection">an class="mw-editsection-bracket">[an><a href="/w/index.php?title=2021_in_American_television&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: February">edita>an class="mw-editsection-bracket">]an>an>

able class="wikitable"> Date Event Source an="2">1 <a href="/wiki/Gray_Television" title="Gray Television">Gray Televisiona> announces its intent to acquire <a href="/wiki/Quincy_Media" title="Quincy Media">Quincy Mediaa>'s broadcasting properties for $925 million. The deal--which was completed on August 2--saw Gray acquire eleven television (and two radio) stations- which was to have expanded its portfolio to 198 TV outlets in 102 <a href="/wiki/Media_market" title="Media market">marketsa> with a collective reach of 25.4% of U.S. television households (as estimated prior to Gray's purchase of 16 additional stations from <a href="/wiki/Meredith_Corporation" title="Meredith Corporation">Meredith Local Mediaa>- see May 3 entry). The expanded portfolio would not include stations Gray had to divest to alleviate market conflicts with existing Gray properties (see April 29 entry). Quincy's newspaper holdings were sold to Phillips Media Group in a separate transaction announced on February 13. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">[13]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">[14]a>
ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">[15]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-qhwsale-16">[16]a> <a href="/wiki/Marilyn_Manson" title="Marilyn Manson">Marilyn Mansona> is dropped from future episodes of <a href="/wiki/American_Gods_(TV_series)" title="American Gods (TV series)">American Godsa> and <a href="/wiki/Creepshow_(TV_series)" title="Creepshow (TV series)">Creepshowa> due to multiple abuse allegations against him. The following day- <a href="/wiki/Creative_Artists_Agency" title="Creative Artists Agency">Creative Artists Agencya> announced that it had dropped Manson as a client. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">[17]a> 3 Country music channel <a href="/wiki/CMT_(American_TV_channel)" title="CMT (American TV channel)">CMTa> joins numerous country radio stations- including those owned by <a href="/wiki/Cumulus_Media" title="Cumulus Media">Cumulus Mediaa> and <a href="/wiki/IHeartMedia" title="IHeartMedia">iHeartMediaa> among others- in pulling <a href="/wiki/Morgan_Wallen" title="Morgan Wallen">Morgan Wallena>'s music from its video library after he was captured on video saying a racial slur that was posted by <a href="/wiki/TMZ" title="TMZ">TMZa>. In addition- he was dropped from his record labels- <a href="/wiki/Big_Loud" title="Big Loud">Big Louda> and <a href="/wiki/Republic_Records" title="Republic Records">Republic Recordsa> along with being pulled from consideration for the <a href="/wiki/Academy_of_Country_Music_Awards" title="Academy of Country Music Awards">Academy of Country Music Awardsa>. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">[18]a> 5 <a href="/wiki/Fox_Business" title="Fox Business">Fox Businessa> cancels <a href="/wiki/Lou_Dobbs_Tonight" title="Lou Dobbs Tonight">Lou Dobbs Tonighta>- the network's highest-rated show. The cancellation came one day after its host- <a href="/wiki/Lou_Dobbs" title="Lou Dobbs">Lou Dobbsa>- was one of several Fox hosts -- and Fox itself -- were sued for $2.7 billion by electronic voting system producer <a href="/wiki/Smartmatic" title="Smartmatic">Smartmatica> for <a href="/wiki/Defamation" title="Defamation">defamationa>- regarding Dobbs and others' role in spreading <a href="/wiki/Attempts_to_overturn_the_2020_United_States_presidential_election#Conspiracy_allegations" title="Attempts to overturn the 2020 United States presidential election">conspiracy theoriesa> about the <a href="/wiki/2020_United_States_presidential_election" title="2020 United States presidential election">2020 United States presidential electiona>. Fox News hosts <a href="/wiki/Maria_Bartiromo" title="Maria Bartiromo">Maria Bartiromoa> and <a href="/wiki/Jeanine_Pirro" title="Jeanine Pirro">Jeanine Pirroa> and frequent Fox News guests and ex-President Donald Trump's former lawyers <a href="/wiki/Rudy_Giuliani" title="Rudy Giuliani">Rudy Giuliania> and <a href="/wiki/Sidney_Powell" title="Sidney Powell">Sidney Powella> were also named in the suit. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dobbs_Cancel_Times-19">[19]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dobbs_Deadline-20">[20]a>
ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dobbs_TVLine-21">[21]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Dobbs_CNNB-22">[22]a> 7 The <a href="/wiki/2020_Tampa_Bay_Buccaneers_season" title="2020 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season">Tampa Bay Buccaneersa> defeat the <a href="/wiki/2020_Kansas_City_Chiefs_season" title="2020 Kansas City Chiefs season">Kansas City Chiefsa> to win <a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_LV" title="Super Bowl LV">Super Bowl LVa> and become the first team to win the championship game in their home stadium. The game aired on CBS in English and ESPN Deportes in Spanish. The game was watched by 90.8 million people on linear television and another 5.6 million people on streaming platforms. It was the smallest audience since <a href="/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXIX" title="Super Bowl XXXIX">Super Bowl XXXIXa> in 2005. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">[23]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">[24]a> 10 <a href="/wiki/Gina_Carano" title="Gina Carano">Gina Caranoa> is fired from <a href="/wiki/The_Mandalorian" title="The Mandalorian">The Mandaloriana> due to her controversial social media posts- with <a href="/wiki/Lucasfilm" title="Lucasfilm">Lucasfilma> announcing that they are ending their relationship with her. Carano is also dropped by <a href="/wiki/United_Talent_Agency" title="United Talent Agency">United Talent Agencya> as a client. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">[25]a> 24 <a href="/wiki/NBC" title="NBC">NBCa> pulls from digital distribution an episode of the medical drama <a href="/wiki/Nurses_(Canadian_TV_series)" title="Nurses (Canadian TV series)">Nursesa> that aired on the network on February 9. Titled "Achilles Heel-" a plotline in the episode features an <a href="/wiki/Orthodox_Judaism" title="Orthodox Judaism">Orthodox Jewisha> patient and his father objecting to a bone graft from a cadaver to treat a leg injury; the characters' depiction received criticism from Jewish rights groups for "demonizing" those of the Jewish faith- and of the ethical quandary presented in the plot being completely fictional. The episode of the Canadian-produced Nurses had already aired in that country in February 2020 (host network <a href="/wiki/Global_Television_Network" title="Global Television Network">Globala> would follow NBC's suit in pulling "Achilles Heel" from its own digital platforms). ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">[26]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-27">[27]a> 28 The <a href="/wiki/78th_Golden_Globe_Awards" title="78th Golden Globe Awards">78th Golden Globe Awardsa> aired on NBC with <a href="/wiki/Tina_Fey" title="Tina Fey">Tina Feya> and <a href="/wiki/Amy_Poehler" title="Amy Poehler">Amy Poehlera> as the hosts. The <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic_in_the_United_States" title="COVID-19 pandemic in the United States">COVID-19 pandemica> moved it from its usual first Sunday of January berth- along with <a href="/wiki/Film_awards_seasons" title="Film awards seasons">film awards seasona> in general. <a href="/wiki/Jane_Fonda" title="Jane Fonda">Jane Fondaa> was honored with the <a href="/wiki/Golden_Globe_Cecil_B._DeMille_Award" title="Golden Globe Cecil B. DeMille Award">Golden Globe Cecil B. DeMille Awarda>. <a href="/wiki/Norman_Lear" title="Norman Lear">Norman Leara> was honored with the <a href="/wiki/Carol_Burnett_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Carol Burnett Award">Carol Burnett Awarda>. This was the first Golden Globe Awards ceremony to go bicoastal with Fey co-hosting from the <a href="/wiki/Rainbow_Room" title="Rainbow Room">Rainbow Rooma> in <a href="/wiki/New_York_City" title="New York City">New York Citya>- and Poehler co-hosting from <a href="/wiki/The_Beverly_Hilton" title="The Beverly Hilton">The Beverly Hiltona> in <a href="/wiki/Beverly_Hills-_California" title="Beverly Hills- California">Beverly Hills- Californiaa>. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-28">[28]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">[29]a>
ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">[30]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">[31]a> able>

an class="mw-headline" id="March">Marchan>an class="mw-editsection">an class="mw-editsection-bracket">[an><a href="/w/index.php?title=2021_in_American_television&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: March">edita>an class="mw-editsection-bracket">]an>an>

able class="wikitable"> Date Event Source an="2">7 TV series <a href="/wiki/Ted_Lasso" title="Ted Lasso">Ted Lassoa> and <a href="/wiki/The_Crown_(TV_series)" title="The Crown (TV series)">The Crowna> and the motion picture <a href="/wiki/Nomadland_(film)" class="mw-redirect" title="Nomadland (film)">Nomadlanda> are among notable winners at the <a href="/wiki/26th_Critics%27_Choice_Awards" title="26th Critics' Choice Awards">26th Critics' Choice Awardsa>. The event aired on <a href="/wiki/The_CW" title="The CW">The CWa>- with <a href="/wiki/Taye_Diggs" title="Taye Diggs">Taye Diggsa> hosting for the third consecutive year. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">[32]a> In <a href="/wiki/Oprah_with_Meghan_and_Harry" title="Oprah with Meghan and Harry">a two-hour speciala> airing on <a href="/wiki/CBS" title="CBS">CBSa>- <a href="/wiki/Prince_Harry-_Duke_of_Sussex" title="Prince Harry- Duke of Sussex">Harrya> and <a href="/wiki/Meghan-_Duchess_of_Sussex" title="Meghan- Duchess of Sussex">Meghana>- the Duke and Duchess of Sussex- talk with <a href="/wiki/Oprah_Winfrey" title="Oprah Winfrey">Oprah Winfreya> about their <a href="/wiki/Megxit" title="Megxit">separationa> as working members of- and relationships with- the <a href="/wiki/British_royal_family" title="British royal family">British royal familya>. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">[33]a> an="2">10 The <a href="/wiki/National_Hockey_League" title="National Hockey League">National Hockey Leaguea> announces a new seven-year deal with <a href="/wiki/ESPN" title="ESPN">ESPNa>- covering the 2021--22 through 2027--28 seasons. Stanton">Louis Stantona> denied the streaming service a summary judgment that would have exempted it from copyright liability; the ruling set up a likely trial in 2022 for an <a href="/wiki/Copyright_infringement" title="Copyright infringement">infringementa> lawsuit filed in 2019 by the owners of <a href="/wiki/Comcast" title="Comcast">NBCa>- <a href="/wiki/The_Walt_Disney_Company" title="The Walt Disney Company">ABCa>- <a href="/wiki/ViacomCBS" class="mw-redirect" title="ViacomCBS">CBSa> and <a href="/wiki/Fox_Corporation" title="Fox Corporation">Foxa>. Locast contended it was exempt from liability under the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Copyright_Act" class="mw-redirect" title="United States Copyright Act">Copyright Acta> because it seeks $5 monthly donations from users--earning around $4.3 million to date- nearly twice the $2.4 million it incurred in operational expenses--to cover costs of "maintaining and operating an expanding system" that streams retransmitted broadcast signals to users within the <a href="/wiki/Media_market" title="Media market">marketsa> it operates. Stanton asserted the donations amounted to surcharges to allow Locast users to receive uninterrupted streams following a 15-minute free viewing window (occurring four times per hour until a donation is made- a feature it suspended on September 1 in light of the ruling)- and asserted no provision exists that would allow the donations to be used for expansion of the service into additional markets. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-170">[170]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-171">[171]a>

ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-192">[192]a> 27 In an unusual move- <a href="/wiki/KATU_(TV)" title="KATU (TV)">KATUa>/<a href="/wiki/Portland-_Oregon" title="Portland- Oregon">Portland- ORa> has what one staffer terms a "No News Monday": The morning- afternoon- and early evening newscasts at the <a href="/wiki/Sinclair_Broadcast_Group" title="Sinclair Broadcast Group">Sinclair Broadcast Groupa>-owned <a href="/wiki/American_Broadcasting_Company" title="American Broadcasting Company">ABCa> affiliate are cancelled for the day (rebroadcasts of KATU-produced specials air in their place) so that the station's news staff can attend a seminar designed to deal with job-related trauma and stress. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-193">[193]a> an="2">29 Xavier Prather becomes the first Black HouseGuest to win the main U.S. version of <a href="/wiki/Big_Brother_(American_TV_series)" title="Big Brother (American TV series)">Big Brothera>- defeating Derek Frazier (son of the late <a href="/wiki/Joe_Frazier" title="Joe Frazier">Joe Fraziera>) for the $750-000 grand prize (increased from $250-000 in past seasons) by a unanimous 9--0 vote of its "jury" of evicted contestants in the <a href="/wiki/Big_Brother_23_(American_season)" title="Big Brother 23 (American season)">Season 23a> finale. (<a href="/wiki/Fox_Broadcasting_Company" title="Fox Broadcasting Company">Foxa>- which has programmed Saturdays since July 1987- was the last network to start offering a full weekly schedule upon adding prime-time programming on Tuesdays and Wednesdays in January 1993; CW predecessors <a href="/wiki/The_WB" title="The WB">The WBa> and <a href="/wiki/UPN" title="UPN">UPNa> never programmed Saturday prime time during their existences.) (which was sanctioned by the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Department_of_the_Treasury" title="United States Department of the Treasury">U.S. Treasury Departmenta> in 2019)- and to have breached the stations- internal broadcasting systems by disseminating the Macaw ransomware strain (linked to an October 10 cyberattack on <a href="/wiki/Olympus_Corporation" title="Olympus Corporation">Olympus Corporationa>) via an interconnected <a href="/wiki/Active_Directory" title="Active Directory">Active Directorya> domain linked across Sinclair's internal network. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-210">[210]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-211">[211]a>

The sale was completed on April 14- 2023. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-246">[245]a> In response to the growth of streaming television- the <a href="/wiki/Academy_of_Television_Arts_%26_Sciences" title="Academy of Television Arts &amp; Sciences">Academy of Television Arts &amp; Sciencesa> and the <a href="/wiki/National_Academy_of_Television_Arts_and_Sciences" title="National Academy of Television Arts and Sciences">National Academy of Television Arts and Sciencesa> announce a major realignment of the <a href="/wiki/Daytime_Emmy_Awards" title="Daytime Emmy Awards">Daytimea> and <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Awards" title="Primetime Emmy Awards">Primetime Emmysa>. Beginning in 2022- the two ceremonies' scopes revolve around factors such as the themes and frequency of such programming- rather than strictly follow whether programs air in daytime or primetime. Among the major changes- daytime dramas- as defined as "any multi-camera- weekday daily serial- spin-off or reboot"- remain in the Daytime Emmys but all other drama programs move to the Primetime Emmys. All children's programming moves to the newly created <a href="/wiki/Children%27s_%26_Family_Emmy_Awards" class="mw-redirect" title="Children's &amp; Family Emmy Awards">Children's &amp; Family Emmy Awardsa>. Morning shows move from the Daytime Emmys to the <a href="/wiki/News_%26_Documentary_Emmy_Awards" class="mw-redirect" title="News &amp; Documentary Emmy Awards">News &amp; Documentary Emmysa>. Talk shows will now be divided between the Daytime and Primetime Emmys based on "format and style characteristics reflective of current programming in the daytime or late night space". ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-247">[246]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-248">[247]a> 15 <a href="/wiki/Jeff_Garlin" title="Jeff Garlin">Jeff Garlina> exits his role of family patriarch Murray Goldberg on the <a href="/wiki/American_Broadcasting_Company" title="American Broadcasting Company">ABCa> sitcom <a href="/wiki/The_Goldbergs_(2013_TV_series)" title="The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)">The Goldbergsa> following multiple misconduct allegations and human resources investigations. The 2022 edition marked the special's 50th anniversary (it premiered on NBC in 1971- and moved to ABC in 1974)- and was the first to feature midnight celebrations for the <a href="/wiki/Atlantic_Time_Zone" title="Atlantic Time Zone">Atlantic Time Zonea> (along with being the <a href="/wiki/ABC_News" title="ABC News">networka>'s first Atlantic Time countdown since the day-long <a href="/wiki/Millennium_celebrations" title="Millennium celebrations">millennium telecasta> <a href="/wiki/ABC_2000_Today" title="ABC 2000 Today">ABC 2000 Todaya>- which aired in place of Rockin' Eve in 1999)- as well as a Spanish-language countdown (presented from San Juan)- in addition to the <a href="/wiki/Times_Square_Ball" title="Times Square Ball">Times Square Balla> and New Orleans <a href="/wiki/Fleur-de-lis" title="Fleur-de-lis">fleur-de-lisa> <a href="/wiki/List_of_objects_dropped_on_New_Year%27s_Eve" title="List of objects dropped on New Year's Eve">dropsa>. (The Puerto Rico countdown was interrupted on some ABC stations in the Eastern and Central Time Zones by late local programming in the 11:00/10:00 slot.) The special featured performances by headliners <a href="/wiki/Ashanti_(singer)" title="Ashanti (singer)">Ashantia>- <a href="/wiki/Ja_Rule" title="Ja Rule">Ja Rulea> and <a href="/wiki/Journey_(band)" title="Journey (band)">Journeya> (the latter becoming the first group or band to serve as the show's midnight headline performer since <a href="/wiki/NKOTBSB" title="NKOTBSB">NKOTBSBa>--the combined <a href="/wiki/Backstreet_Boys" title="Backstreet Boys">Backstreet Boysa> and <a href="/wiki/New_Kids_on_the_Block" title="New Kids on the Block">New Kids on the Blocka>--performed in the 2011 edition) as well as- among others- <a href="/wiki/Daddy_Yankee" title="Daddy Yankee">Daddy Yankeea>- <a href="/wiki/OneRepublic" title="OneRepublic">OneRepublica>- <a href="/wiki/Avril_Lavigne" title="Avril Lavigne">Avril Lavignea>- <a href="/wiki/Travis_Barker" title="Travis Barker">Travis Barkera> and <a href="/wiki/Macklemore_%26_Ryan_Lewis" title="Macklemore &amp; Ryan Lewis">Macklemore &amp; Ryan Lewisa>. (<a href="/wiki/LL_Cool_J" title="LL Cool J">LL Cool Ja>- due to contracting COVID-19; and <a href="/wiki/Chloe_Bailey" title="Chloe Bailey">Chlöea> and <a href="/wiki/Karol_G" title="Karol G">Karol Ga>- both for unspecified reasons- respectively cancelled their scheduled performances prior to broadcast.) The 2022 edition is also the first not to be produced by <a href="/wiki/Dick_Clark_Productions" title="Dick Clark Productions">Dick Clark Productionsa>- which <a href="/wiki/MRC_(company)" title="MRC (company)">MRCa> (which began producing Rockin- Eve through its MRC Live &amp; Alternative unit with that broadcast) discontinued as a studio <a href="/wiki/Imprint_(trade_name)" title="Imprint (trade name)">imprinta> in September 2021. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-264">[263]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-265">[264]a>
ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-266">[265]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-267">[266]a>
ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-268">[267]a> After a 21-year absence- <a href="/wiki/CBS" title="CBS">CBSa> returned to broadcasting <a href="/wiki/New_Year%27s_Eve" title="New Year's Eve">New Year's Evea> <a href="/wiki/Television_special" title="Television special">live programminga> with New Year's Eve Live: Nashville's Big Bash- broadcast live from the <a href="/wiki/Bicentennial_Capitol_Mall_State_Park" title="Bicentennial Capitol Mall State Park">Bicentennial Capitol Mall State Parka> in <a href="/wiki/Nashville-_Tennessee" title="Nashville- Tennessee">downtown Nashville- Tennesseea>- and various locations across the city. Hosted by <a href="/wiki/Bobby_Bones" title="Bobby Bones">Bobby Bonesa> and <a href="/wiki/Rachel_Smith" title="Rachel Smith">Rachel Smitha>- the special featured performances by headliners <a href="/wiki/Lady_A" title="Lady A">Lady Aa>- <a href="/wiki/Dierks_Bentley" title="Dierks Bentley">Dierks Bentleya>- <a href="/wiki/Dan_%2B_Shay" title="Dan + Shay">Dan + Shaya>- <a href="/wiki/Blake_Shelton" title="Blake Shelton">Blake Sheltona>- <a href="/wiki/Miranda_Lambert" title="Miranda Lambert">Miranda Lamberta>- <a href="/wiki/Brooks_%26_Dunn" title="Brooks &amp; Dunn">Brooks &amp; Dunna>- among others- as well as the event's renowned <a href="/wiki/Musical_note" title="Musical note">music notea> <a href="/wiki/List_of_objects_dropped_on_New_Year%27s_Eve" title="List of objects dropped on New Year's Eve">dropa> and <a href="/wiki/Fireworks" title="Fireworks">fireworks displaya> at midnight (<a href="/wiki/Central_Time_Zone" title="Central Time Zone">CTa>). (Three other scheduled acts canceled their performances the day before the broadcast: <a href="/wiki/Sam_Hunt" title="Sam Hunt">Sam Hunta> and <a href="/wiki/Elle_King" title="Elle King">Elle Kinga>- due to unspecified COVID-19 protocols; and the <a href="/wiki/Zac_Brown_Band" title="Zac Brown Band">Zac Brown Banda>- due to <a href="/wiki/Zac_Brown" title="Zac Brown">Browna> re-contracting COVID-19 following a prior bout in August.) This marked the network's first New Year's Eve special and the fourth one since America's Millennium (broadcast in 1999)- and its predecessors <a href="/wiki/Happy_New_Year-_America" title="Happy New Year- America">Happy New Year- Americaa> (broadcast from 1979 to 1995) and <a href="/wiki/Guy_Lombardo" title="Guy Lombardo">New Year's Eve With Guy Lombardoa> (broadcast from 1956 to 1978). ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-269">[268]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-270">[269]a>
ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-271">[270]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-272">[271]a> <a href="/wiki/NBC_New_Year%27s_Eve_specials#Miley's_New_Year's_Eve_Party" title="NBC New Year's Eve specials">Miley's New Year's Eve Partya> airs on NBC- hosted by <a href="/wiki/Miley_Cyrus" title="Miley Cyrus">Miley Cyrusa> and <a href="/wiki/Pete_Davidson" title="Pete Davidson">Pete Davidsona>; and featuring performances by <a href="/wiki/24kGoldn" title="24kGoldn">24kGoldna>- <a href="/wiki/Anitta_(singer)" title="Anitta (singer)">Anittaa>- <a href="/wiki/Billie_Joe_Armstrong" title="Billie Joe Armstrong">Billie Joe Armstronga>- <a href="/wiki/Brandi_Carlile" title="Brandi Carlile">Brandi Carlilea>- <a href="/wiki/Jack_Harlow" title="Jack Harlow">Jack Harlowa>- Kitty Cash- and <a href="/wiki/Saweetie" title="Saweetie">Saweetiea>. The two-hour special--which replaced the <a href="/wiki/Carson_Daly" title="Carson Daly">Carson Dalya>-led NBC's New Year's Eve specials aired from 2004 to 2020- and was not split between prime time and late-night segments- with late local programming being moved to an hour earlier (which resulted in scheduling conflicts involving local <a href="/wiki/Late-night_news" class="mw-redirect" title="Late-night news">late-night newscastsa>- many of which were simulcast on the partner outlet to compensate- in certain markets where an NBC-affiliated station produces a separate primetime newscast for a non-<a href="/wiki/Big_Three_television_network" class="mw-redirect" title="Big Three television network">Big Threea> network affiliate- an <a href="/wiki/Independent_station_(North_America)" class="mw-redirect" title="Independent station (North America)">independent stationa> or a <a href="/wiki/Digital_subchannel" title="Digital subchannel">subchannela>)--was developed as part of an overall content and development deal between Cyrus and NBCUniversal signed on May 14. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-273">[272]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-274">[273]a>
ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-275">[274]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-276">[275]a> <a href="/wiki/Peter_Roth_(executive)" title="Peter Roth (executive)">Peter Rotha> steps down as the chairman of <a href="/wiki/Warner_Bros._Television_Studios" title="Warner Bros. Television Studios">Warner Bros. Television Groupa> and is succeeded by <a href="/wiki/Channing_Dungey" title="Channing Dungey">Channing Dungeya>. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-277">[276]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-278">[277]a> able>

an class="mw-headline" id="Entering_syndication_in_2021">Entering syndication in 2021an>an class="mw-editsection">an class="mw-editsection-bracket">[an><a href="/w/index.php?title=2021_in_American_television&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Entering syndication in 2021">edita>an class="mw-editsection-bracket">]an>an>

an class="mw-headline" id="Networks_and_services">Networks and servicesan>an class="mw-editsection">an class="mw-editsection-bracket">[an><a href="/w/index.php?title=2021_in_American_television&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Networks and services">edita>an class="mw-editsection-bracket">]an>an>

an class="mw-headline" id="Launches">Launchesan>an class="mw-editsection">an class="mw-editsection-bracket">[an><a href="/w/index.php?title=2021_in_American_television&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Launches">edita>an class="mw-editsection-bracket">]an>an>

able class="wikitable"> Network Type Launch date Notes Source <a href="/wiki/Discovery%2B" title="Discovery+">Discovery+a> OTT streaming January 4 Announced in September 2020 as a global expansion of its existing <a href="/wiki/India" title="India">Indiaa> service (launched in March of that year)- <a href="/wiki/Discovery-_Inc." title="Discovery- Inc.">Discovery- Inc.a> launched Discovery+ as a streaming service featuring original and archival content from Discovery's network and production properties (including the former networks of <a href="/wiki/Scripps_Networks_Interactive" title="Scripps Networks Interactive">Scripps Networks Interactivea> acquired by the company in March 2018) as well as select programming from <a href="/wiki/A%26E_Networks" title="A&amp;E Networks">A&amp;E Networksa>. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-570">[567]a> <a href="/wiki/Twist_(TV_network)" title="Twist (TV network)">Twista> an="4">OTA multicast April 5 Tegna revealed plans on February 24 to launch Twist- which joins <a href="/wiki/True_Crime_Network" title="True Crime Network">True Crime Networka> and <a href="/wiki/Quest_(American_TV_network)" title="Quest (American TV network)">Questa> in the company's multicast portfolio. Twist targets a female audience with <a href="/wiki/Factual_television" title="Factual television">factual lifestylea> and <a href="/wiki/Reality_television" title="Reality television">realitya> programming- mainly home- and food-oriented shows sourced from the libraries of A&amp;E Networks and <a href="/wiki/NBCUniversal_Television_and_Streaming" title="NBCUniversal Television and Streaming">NBCUniversal Lifestyle Network Groupa>. The "exciting reveals" featured in these shows serve as the inspiration for the network's name. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto5-571">[568]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-auto6-572">[569]a> <a href="/wiki/MeTV#MeTV_Plus" title="MeTV">MeTV+a> May 15 On May 3- <a href="/wiki/Weigel_Broadcasting" title="Weigel Broadcasting">Weigel Broadcastinga> announced plans to launch MeTV+- an experimental spin-off of flagship network <a href="/wiki/MeTV" title="MeTV">MeTVa> with a lineup of classic sitcoms- drama series- and <a href="/wiki/Short_film" title="Short film">comedic and animated shortsa> sourced from the libraries of <a href="/wiki/Sony_Pictures_Television" title="Sony Pictures Television">Sony Pictures Televisiona>- <a href="/wiki/CBS_Media_Ventures" title="CBS Media Ventures">CBS Media Venturesa>- <a href="/wiki/Warner_Bros._Television" class="mw-redirect" title="Warner Bros. Television">Warner Bros. Domestic Television Distributiona> and <a href="/wiki/NBCUniversal_Syndication_Studios" title="NBCUniversal Syndication Studios">NBCUniversal Syndication Studiosa> complementary to the offerings on its parent network. At the outset- MeTV+--the second MeTV extension effort by Weigel- following a local "MeToo" service that ran on <a href="/wiki/WMEU-CD" title="WMEU-CD">WMEU-CDa>/Chicago (now an <a href="/wiki/Independent_station_(North_America)" class="mw-redirect" title="Independent station (North America)">independent stationa>) from 2008 to 2013--launched on Weigel-owned Chicago flagship <a href="/wiki/WCIU-TV" title="WCIU-TV">WCIU-TVa> and <a href="/wiki/KMOH-TV" title="KMOH-TV">KMOH-TVa>/<a href="/wiki/Kingman-_Arizona" title="Kingman- Arizona">Kingmana>--<a href="/wiki/Phoenix-_Arizona" title="Phoenix- Arizona">Phoenixa>- occupying subchannels that carried <a href="/wiki/Bounce_TV" title="Bounce TV">Bounce TVa> (which shifted to local <a href="/wiki/Ion_(TV_network)" class="mw-redirect" title="Ion (TV network)">Iona> stations owned by the <a href="/wiki/E._W._Scripps_Company" title="E. W. Scripps Company">E. W. Scripps Companya>- parent of Bounce owner <a href="/wiki/Katz_Broadcasting" title="Katz Broadcasting">Katz Broadcastinga>). If successful- Weigel plans to expand MeTV+ to stations that the company owns in other markets (including as a replacement for Bounce TV on Weigel stations that carried the network since its 2011 debut) and to affiliates owned by third-party station groups. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-rfeder-metvplus-573">[570]a> <a href="/wiki/Defy_TV" title="Defy TV">Defy TVa> an="2">July 1 an="2">On March 2- the E. W. W. Scripps Company">E. W. Scripps Companya> announced the shuttering of three Ion networks -- Ion Plus (a secondary schedule of programming from Ion's content distributors)- Ion Shop (<a href="/wiki/Infomercial" title="Infomercial">all-paid programminga>) and Qubo (children's programming) -- and allocate their spectrum space on Ion Media's stations to offer networks from existing Scripps subsidiary <a href="/wiki/Katz_Broadcasting" title="Katz Broadcasting">Katz Broadcastinga> (consisting of <a href="/wiki/Court_TV" title="Court TV">Court TVa>- <a href="/wiki/Court_TV_Mystery" class="mw-redirect" title="Court TV Mystery">Court TV Mysterya>- <a href="/wiki/Bounce_TV" title="Bounce TV">Bounce TVa>- <a href="/wiki/Laff_(TV_network)" title="Laff (TV network)">Laffa> and <a href="/wiki/Grit_(TV_network)" title="Grit (TV network)">Grita>). This eventually consolidates Ion's operations into Katz and replace expiring contracts with other broadcasters that carried the Katz networks outside of mainstream Scripps markets (albeit with affiliate duplication in the interim due to the structure of Katz's subchannel-leasing arrangements)- while offloading those networks on mainstream Scripps stations with limited spectrum capacity during the <a href="/wiki/ATSC_3.0" title="ATSC 3.0">ATSC 3.0a> transition. (Ion's <a href="/wiki/Ion_Television" title="Ion Television">namesake flagship channela> continues as a Scripps-owned network.) Qubo- Ion Plus and Ion Shop were replaced by selected Katz networks on Ion affiliates (consisting mainly of former O&amp;Os spun off by Scripps to Inyo Broadcast Holdings) on February 27- and were replaced on Scripps-owned Ion stations post-shutdown on March 1. an="3">ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ScrippsIon-612">[609]a> <a href="/wiki/Ion_Television#Ion_Shop" title="Ion Television">Ion Shopa> <a href="/wiki/Qubo" title="Qubo">Quboa> <a href="/wiki/WWE_Network" title="WWE Network">WWE Networka> OTT streaming March 18
(United States) On January 25- <a href="/wiki/WWE" title="WWE">WWEa> announced it would discontinue the standalone WWE Network service in the United States and merge it into the offerings of <a href="/wiki/Peacock_(streaming_service)" title="Peacock (streaming service)">Peacocka>. All paying Peacock subscribers gained access to the <a href="/wiki/WWE_Video_Library" class="mw-redirect" title="WWE Video Library">WWE Video Librarya> and no-cost access to WWE <a href="/wiki/Pay-per-view" title="Pay-per-view">pay-per-viewa> events in the same manner as current WWE Network subscribers. WWE Network remains unchanged outside of the United States. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-613">[610]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-614">[611]a> <a href="/wiki/CNN_Airport" title="CNN Airport">CNN Airporta> <a href="/wiki/Closed-circuit_television" title="Closed-circuit television">Closed-circuita> <a href="/wiki/International_airport" title="International airport">international airporta> television systems March 31 On January 12- <a href="/wiki/CNN" title="CNN">CNNa> announced that it would shut down the CNN Airport network- which was available in numerous airports across the United States. The network- which carried a mixture of family-friendly news and entertainment programs from select <a href="/wiki/WarnerMedia" title="WarnerMedia">WarnerMediaa> networks (as well as some high-profile sporting events)- had been seeing declining viewership since the <a href="/wiki/Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%9308" class="mw-redirect" title="Financial crisis of 2007--08">financial crisis of 2007--08a> as a result of the increased proliferation of <a href="/wiki/Wi-Fi" title="Wi-Fi">Wi-Fia>-enabled devices which themselves allow access to the mainline CNN network; the decline was accelerated in 2020 when global <a href="/wiki/Commercial_air_travel" class="mw-redirect" title="Commercial air travel">commercial air travela> <a href="/wiki/Impact_of_the_COVID-19_pandemic_on_aviation" class="mw-redirect" title="Impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on aviation">declined greatlya> as a result of the <a href="/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic" title="COVID-19 pandemic">COVID-19 pandemica>. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-615">[612]a> <a href="/wiki/NBC_Sports_Northwest" title="NBC Sports Northwest">NBC Sports Northwesta> Cable and satellite September 30 On June 9- NBC Sports Group announced it was shutting down NBC Sports Northwest- which launched in 2007 as Comcast SportsNet Northwest and later rebranded as CSN Northwest in 2012 and to NBC Sports Northwest in 2017. The closure came after the <a href="/wiki/Portland_Trail_Blazers" title="Portland Trail Blazers">Portland Trail Blazersa> (a key team part of the network's programming since its inception) signed a four-year deal with <a href="/wiki/Root_Sports_Northwest" title="Root Sports Northwest">Root Sports Northwesta> on the same date. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-616">[613]a> <a href="/wiki/Hotstar" class="mw-redirect" title="Hotstar">Hotstara>
an style="font-size:85%;">(U.S. only)an> OTT streaming November 30 On August 31- 2021- Disney announced that the U.S. version of Hotstar--targeted domestically at mainly <a href="/wiki/Indian_Americans" title="Indian Americans">American-borna> and <a href="/wiki/Non-resident_Indian_and_Overseas_Citizen_of_India" class="mw-redirect" title="Non-resident Indian and Overseas Citizen of India">expatriate Indiansa>--would cease operations as a standalone platform by around late 2022. On the date of the announcement- <a href="/wiki/Bollywood" class="mw-redirect" title="Bollywood">Bollywooda> and <a href="/wiki/South_Asia" title="South Asia">South Asiana> films- television series and original specials featured in Hotstar's U.S. catalog (which will be rotated on and off at regular intervals) were added to <a href="/wiki/Hulu" title="Hulu">Hulua>- while the service's rights to <a href="/wiki/Indian_Premier_League" title="Indian Premier League">Indian Premier Leaguea>- <a href="/wiki/ICC_Men%27s_T20_World_Cup" title="ICC Men's T20 World Cup">ICC Men's T20 World Cupa> and <a href="/wiki/Board_of_Control_for_Cricket_in_India" title="Board of Control for Cricket in India">BCCIa>-sanctioned <a href="/wiki/Cricket" title="Cricket">cricketa> competitions were incorporated into <a href="/wiki/ESPN%2B" title="ESPN+">ESPN+a>. Hotstar (alternately branded as Disney+ Hotstar in Asia) will continue to operate in parts of South Asia (specifically India- Indonesia- Malaysia- Thailand and Singapore)- Canada and the United Kingdom. The closure date was brought forward by over a year with less than 2 weeks' notice on November 18- 2021. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-617">[614]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-618">[615]a> <a href="/wiki/ESPN_Classic" title="ESPN Classic">ESPN Classica> an="3">Cable and satellite an="3">December 31 On November 4- ESPN confirmed the closure of the network- originally launched as Classic Sports Network in 1995 before its 1997 acquisition by ESPN. The network had already lost library programming over the years and was slowly wound down as ESPN had allowed various providers to drop the network in <a href="/wiki/Retransmission_consent" title="Retransmission consent">retransmission consenta> negotiations since the mid-2010s in order to pick up new ESPN networks as replacements. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-619">[616]a> <a href="/wiki/Fusion_TV" title="Fusion TV">Fusion TVa> On December 4- <a href="/wiki/Univision_Communications" class="mw-redirect" title="Univision Communications">Univision Communicationsa> confirmed through notice to its remaining providers the closure of Fusion- originally launched in October 2013 with a focus on <a href="/wiki/24-hour_news_cycle" title="24-hour news cycle">newsa>- lifestyle- <a href="/wiki/Popular_culture" title="Popular culture">pop culturea>- satire and entertainment programs aimed at English-speaking <a href="/wiki/Millennials" title="Millennials">millennialsa>- including those of a <a href="/wiki/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans" title="Hispanic and Latino Americans">Hispanic backgrounda>. The network--which was founded as a joint venture between Univision and <a href="/wiki/The_Walt_Disney_Company" title="The Walt Disney Company">The Walt Disney Companya> (through <a href="/wiki/ABC_News" title="ABC News">ABC Newsa>)- the latter which sold its stake in 2016--struggled to maintain a consistent programming identity (experiencing heavy churn of its news and documentary programs- while shifting more toward a documentary and entertainment format in its waning years); to obtain widespread distribution across wireline- satellite and live-TV streaming providers; and to attract sufficient viewership in its target demographic throughout its eight-year existence. Fusion also incurred significant profit losses over its run (incurring deficits of $35 million in 2014 alone) as Univision struggled through an era under the management of <a href="/wiki/Private_equity" title="Private equity">private equitya> which mandated the launch of English-language inroads; the network is currently in the process of merging with longtime content partner <a href="/wiki/Televisa" title="Televisa">Televisaa> and focusing exclusively on Spanish-language audiences. It was the second consecutive year a Univision-funded English-language channel shut down- as <a href="/wiki/El_Rey_Network" title="El Rey Network">El Rey Networka>'s wireline network was shut down exactly a year before- several months after it spun off its interest in the channel. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-620">[617]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-621">[618]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-622">[619]a> <a href="/wiki/NBCSN" title="NBCSN">NBCSNa> On January 22- NBC Sports Group announced it was shutting down NBCSN- which launched in 1995 as the Outdoor Life Network and later rebranded as Versus before becoming the NBC Sports Network in 2012 and adopting its current name in 2013. Its programming- which includes the <a href="/wiki/Premier_League" title="Premier League">Premier Leaguea> and <a href="/wiki/NASCAR" title="NASCAR">NASCARa> races- moves primarily to <a href="/wiki/NBC" title="NBC">NBCa> and <a href="/wiki/USA_Network" title="USA Network">USA Networka> as well as the <a href="/wiki/Peacock_(streaming_service)" title="Peacock (streaming service)">Peacocka> streaming service. A cornerstone of NBCSN's programming had been the <a href="/wiki/National_Hockey_League" title="National Hockey League">National Hockey Leaguea>- whose contract with NBC Sports expired at the end of the <a href="/wiki/2020%E2%80%9321_NHL_season" title="2020--21 NHL season">abbreviated 2021 seasona>. ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-623">[620]a>ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-624">[621]a> able>

This section outlines affiliation changes involving English and Spanish networks (<a href="/wiki/American_Broadcasting_Company" title="American Broadcasting Company">ABCa>- <a href="/wiki/NBC" title="NBC">NBCa>- <a href="/wiki/CBS" title="CBS">CBSa>- <a href="/wiki/Fox_Broadcasting_Company" title="Fox Broadcasting Company">Foxa>- <a href="/wiki/PBS" title="PBS">PBSa>- <a href="/wiki/The_CW" title="The CW">The CWa>- <a href="/wiki/Univision" title="Univision">Univisiona>- etc.)- and format conversions involving <a href="/wiki/Independent_station_(North_America)" class="mw-redirect" title="Independent station (North America)">independent stationsa>. Digital subchannels are mentioned if the prior or new affiliation involves a major English and Spanish broadcast network or a locally programmed independent entertainment format.

On January 1- WOIO began to produce twice-nightly Monday--Friday newscasts for WTCL- becoming the first Spanish-language local news offering in the Cleveland market (WQHS and WQDI- respectively- have never offered in-house or outsourced local news programming since converting into Spanish stations). ass="reference"><a href="#cite_note-645">[642]a> able>
